<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<LinearLayout xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    xmlns:app="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res-auto"
    xmlns:tools="http://schemas.android.com/tools"
    android:layout_width="match_parent"
    android:layout_height="match_parent"
    android:orientation="vertical"
    tools:context=".law2">

    <ScrollView
        android:layout_width="match_parent"
        android:layout_height="match_parent"
        tools:ignore="SpeakableTextPresentCheck">

        <LinearLayout
            android:layout_width="match_parent"
            android:layout_height="wrap_content"
            android:orientation="vertical" >

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView9"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="2. Special Marriage Act, 1954"

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView6"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                app:srcCompat="@drawable/marriage" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView10"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="The objectives of this act is to provide – a special form of marriage in certain cases, provide for registration of certain marriages and, to provide for divorce. In a country like India and with the diverse religions and cast, when people from different faiths and caste chose to get married they do it under the Special Marriage Act.

It is not applicable to the state of Jammu and Kashmir and also extends to intending spouses who are Indian nationals and living abroad.

"
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView5"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="3. Dowry Prohibition Act, 1961"

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                app:srcCompat="@drawable/dowry" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView7"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="According to this act, taking or giving of dowry at the time of the marriage to the bride or the bridegroom and their family is to be penalised. Dowry system, giving and taking of dowry, is a norm in India. Dowry is often asked of the bride and her family by the groom and his family. The system has taken strong roots because women after marriage move in with their spouse and in-laws. Also, over the centuries, the lack for economic independence of women and the taboo towards divorce has resulted in bride burning. When demands for dowry even after marriage are not met by the girl’s families, many women are tortured, beaten and even burnt.

It is one of the major challenges that our society is grappling with. Women openly complaining about it has helped to spread the word and encourage other women to take a stand."

                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView11"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="4.Indian Divorce Act, 1969 "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView7"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                android:textSize="34sp"

                app:srcCompat="@drawable/divorce" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView12"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="The Indian Divorce Act allows the dissolution of marriage, mutual consent, nullity of marriage, judicial separation and restitution of conjugal rights.

Family Courts are established to file, hear, and dispose of such cases."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView13"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="5. Maternity Benefit Act,1861 "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView8"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                app:srcCompat="@drawable/maternity" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView14"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="This act regulates the employment of women and maternity benefits mandated by law. It states that a woman employee who has worked in an organisation for a period of at least 80 days during the 12 months preceding the date of her expected delivery is entitled to receive maternity benefits, which includes maternity leave, nursing breaks, medical allowance, etc."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView15"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="6. Medical Termination of Pregnancy Act,1971"

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView9"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                app:srcCompat="@drawable/medical" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView16"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="This act regulates the employment of women and maternity benefits mandated by law. It states that a woman employee who has worked in an organisation for a period of at least 80 days during the 12 months preceding the date of her expected delivery is entitled to receive maternity benefits, which includes maternity leave, nursing breaks, medical allowance, etc. "
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView17"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="7. Sexual Harassment of Women at Workplace (Prevention, Prohibition and Redressal) Act, 2013 "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView10"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                android:textSize="34sp"

                app:srcCompat="@drawable/sexual" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView18"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="To ensure women’s safety at workplace, this Act seeks to protect them from sexual harassment at their place of work. Thirty-six percent of Indian companies and 25 percent among MNC’s are not complaint with the Sexual Harassment Act according to a FICCI-EY November 2015 report.

Sexual harassment at workplace also includes – the use of language with sexual overtones, invasion of private space with a male colleague hovering too close for comfort, subtle touches and innuendoes."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView19"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="8. Indecent Representation of Women(Prevention) Act,1986  "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView11"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                android:textSize="34sp"

                app:srcCompat="@drawable/incedent" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView20"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="This Act prohibits indecent representation of women through advertisement or in publications, writings, paintings, figures or in any other manner."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView21"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="9. National Commission for Women Act, 1990 "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView12"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                android:textSize="34sp"

                app:srcCompat="@drawable/national" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView22"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="The National Commission for Women (NCW) is a statutory body of the Government of India, established in January 1992. Lalitha Kumaramangalam was appointed its Chairperson in 2014.

The NCW represents the rights of women in India and provides a voice for their issues and concerns. The National Commission for Women Act aims to improve the status of women and worked for their economic empowerment."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView23"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="10. Equal Remuneration Act, 1976 "

                android:textColor="#F44336"

                android:textSize="34sp" />

            <ImageView
                android:id="@+id/imageView13"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="217dp"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:layout_marginStart="10dp"
                android:layout_marginLeft="10dp"
                android:layout_marginEnd="10dp"
                android:layout_marginRight="10dp"
                android:textSize="34sp"

                app:srcCompat="@drawable/equal" />

            <TextView
                android:id="@+id/textView24"
                android:layout_width="match_parent"
                android:layout_height="wrap_content"
                android:layout_margin="10dp"
                android:padding="5dp"
                android:text="This Act prevents discrimination in terms of remuneration. It provides for payment of equal recompense to men and women workers.

It is necessary to know these and other laws in place to protect the interests of women. Only if you are aware of your rights can you fight against any injustice meted out to you at home, at the workplace, or in the society."
                android:textColor="#030304"
                android:textSize="20sp" />

        </LinearLayout>
    </ScrollView>
</LinearLayout>